Among 3411 ICU admissions, 195 (5.7%) ICU-acquired Enterobacteriaceae bacteraemia cases occurred. Enterobacteriaceae bacteraemia was associated with an increased daily risk of ICU death [cause-specific hazard ratio (HR): 1.48; 95% confidence interval (CI): 1.10–1.99] and a reduced daily risk of ICU discharge (HR: 0.66; 95% CI: 0.54–0.80). Appropriate empiric antibiotic therapy did not significantly modify ICU mortality (HR: 1.08; 95% CI: 0.59–1.97) or discharge (HR: 0.91; 95% CI: 0.63–1.32).
